SIMPLE: stubborn
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stubborn
<hw>Stub"born</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>stoburn</ets>, <ets>stiborn</ets>; probably fr. AS. <ets>styb</ets>
a stub. See <er>Stub</er>.]</ety> <def>Firm as a stub or stump; stiff;
unbending; unyielding; persistent; hence, unreasonably obstinate in will
or opinion; not yielding to reason or persuasion; refractory; harsh; --
said of persons and things; <as>as, <ex>stubborn</ex> wills;
<ex>stubborn</ex> ore; a <ex>stubborn</ex> oak; as <ex>stubborn</ex> as
a mule.</as></def> ⟦ldquo⟧Bow, <xex>stubborn</xex> knees.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Shak.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Stubborn</xex> attention and more than common
application.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Locke.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Stubborn</xex>
Stoics.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Swift.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And I was young and full of ragerie [wantonness]⟦br⟧
<qex>Stubborn</qex> and strong, and jolly as a pie.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These heretics be so stiff and <qex>stubborn</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir T. More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your <qex>stubborn</qex> usage of the pope.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Obstinate; inflexible; obdurate; headstrong;
stiff; hardy; firm; refractory; intractable; rugged; contumacious;
heady.</syn> -- <usage><er>Stubborn</er>, <er>Obstinate</er>.
<xex>Obstinate</xex> is used of either active or passive persistence in
one's views or conduct, in spite of the wishes of others.
<xex>Stubborn</xex> describes an extreme degree of passive
<xex>obstinacy</xex>.</usage> -- <wordforms><wf>Stub"born*ly</wf>,
<pos>adv.</pos> -- <wf>Stub"born*ness</wf>,
<pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stubby</ent>⟦br⟧
